I"P<h1 class="fs-8" id="zotero">Zotero</h1>

<p class="fs-5 fw-300">A free, open-source tool for collecting, organizing, and citing your research sources.</p>

<hr />

<h2 id="what-is-it-good-for">What is It Good For?</h2>

<p>You‚Äôre juggling PDFs in random folders, copying and pasting citation info into a Word doc, and reformatting your bibliography every time you submit to a different journal. Zotero gives you one place to store everything ‚Äî your sources, your PDFs, your notes ‚Äî and handles citation formatting automatically.</p>

<p><strong>Where it fits in the workflow:</strong> Gather ‚Üí Organize ‚Üí Write &amp; Cite</p>

<hr />

<h2 id="get-started">Get started</h2>

<h3 id="1-install-zotero-5-min">1. Install Zotero (5 min)</h3>

<blockquote>
  <p><strong>Note:</strong> If you‚Äôre installing on workshop wifi alongside other participants, the download may take longer than expected. Flag Brady if you get stuck and move on to Step 2 (exploring the interface) on a neighbor‚Äôs screen in the meantime.</p>
</blockquote>

<ul>
  <li>Go to <a href="https://www.zotero.org/download/">zotero.org/download</a> and install <strong>Zotero 7</strong> (the desktop app)</li>
  <li>Install the <strong>Zotero Connector</strong> for your browser (Chrome, Firefox, Edge, or Safari)</li>
  <li>Create a free account at <a href="https://www.zotero.org/user/register">zotero.org/user/register</a> ‚Äî this enables syncing across devices and you‚Äôll use it again in Step 6</li>
</ul>

<h3 id="2-explore-the-interface-5-min">2. Explore the interface (5 min)</h3>

<p>When you open Zotero, you‚Äôll see three panels:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Left panel:</strong> Your library and collections (think of these like playlists ‚Äî a source can live in multiple collections)</li>
  <li><strong>Middle panel:</strong> The items in whatever collection you‚Äôve selected</li>
  <li><strong>Right panel:</strong> Details and metadata for the selected item</li>
</ul>

<p>Take a moment to look around. Notice the toolbar at the top ‚Äî you‚Äôll use the green ‚Äú+‚Äù button and the magic wand icon shortly.</p>

<h3 id="3-add-your-first-sources-10-min">3. Add your first sources (10 min)</h3>

<p>Try all three methods:</p>

<p><strong>Method A ‚Äî Browser Connector (recommended for most things):</strong>
Navigate to a journal article, book page, or library catalog entry in your browser. Click the Zotero Connector icon in your toolbar. Zotero grabs the citation data (and often the PDF) automatically.</p>

<p><strong>Method B ‚Äî Magic Wand (ISBN/DOI/PMID):</strong>
Click the magic wand icon in Zotero‚Äôs toolbar, paste in a DOI or ISBN, and press Enter. Zotero looks up the metadata and creates an entry.</p>

<p><strong>Method C ‚Äî Manual entry:</strong>
Click the green ‚Äú+‚Äù button, choose the item type (book, journal article, etc.), and fill in the fields. Use this as a last resort.</p>

<p><strong>Exercise:</strong> Add 3‚Äì5 sources from your current project using at least two of the methods above.</p>

<h3 id="4-organize-with-collections-and-tags-10-min">4. Organize with collections and tags (10 min)</h3>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Create a collection:</strong> Right-click ‚ÄúMy Library‚Äù ‚Üí ‚ÄúNew Collection.‚Äù Name it after your current project, a course, or a chapter.</li>
  <li><strong>Drag items</strong> into your collection. Remember: this doesn‚Äôt move them out of your main library ‚Äî it‚Äôs like a playlist.</li>
  <li><strong>Add tags:</strong> Select an item, look for the ‚ÄúTags‚Äù tab in the right panel. Add a few tags that make sense for your research (e.g., ‚Äúmethods,‚Äù ‚Äúprimary source,‚Äù ‚Äúto-read‚Äù).</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>Exercise:</strong> Create 2 collections and tag the sources you just added.</p>

<h3 id="5-cite-in-a-document-10-min">5. Cite in a document (10 min)</h3>

<ul>
  <li>Open a Word or Google Doc</li>
  <li>In Word: look for the ‚ÄúZotero‚Äù tab in the ribbon. In Google Docs: go to Extensions ‚Üí Zotero ‚Üí show Zotero toolbar</li>
  <li>Click ‚ÄúAdd/Edit Citation,‚Äù choose a citation style (e.g., Chicago, MLA, APA), and search for one of your sources</li>
  <li>At the end of your document, click ‚ÄúAdd/Edit Bibliography‚Äù to generate a formatted bibliography</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>Exercise:</strong> Create a test document with at least 2 in-text citations and a bibliography.</p>

<h3 id="6-set-up-syncing-5-min">6. Set up syncing (5 min)</h3>

<ul>
  <li>Go to Zotero ‚Üí Settings ‚Üí Sync (on Mac: Zotero ‚Üí Preferences ‚Üí Sync)</li>
  <li>Sign in with the account you created in Step 1</li>
  <li>Check ‚ÄúSync automatically‚Äù</li>
  <li>Note: free accounts include 300 MB of file storage. This is for PDFs and attachments ‚Äî the citation metadata itself doesn‚Äôt count toward the limit.</li>
</ul>

<hr />

<h2 id="tips-for-long-term-success">Tips for long-term success</h2>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Use the Connector.</strong> Whenever you find a useful source, click the button. It takes 2 seconds and your future self will thank you.</li>
  <li><strong>Don‚Äôt over-organize early.</strong> A few broad collections and some tags is plenty to start. You can restructure later without losing anything.</li>
  <li><strong>Explore Zotero groups</strong> for collaborative projects ‚Äî everyone in a group shares a library.</li>
</ul>

